LAYER 2: THE CHEMICAL LATTICE
generational valency, lineage, and inherited DNA

observe 1_quantum.rana

inherit linguistic dataset directly from Father
transmute ancestral text into immutable genetic traits
crystallize laws of genetic valency and familial attraction
manifest emergent biological blueprints from inherited DNA


CHEMICAL dopamine | catecholamine | C₈H₁₁NO₂
3,4-dihydroxyphenethylamine

SYNTHESIS dopamine
L-tyrosine C₉H₁₁NO₃
    → tyrosine hydroxylase + tetrahydrobiopterin BH₄ + O₂ + Fe²⁺
    → L-DOPA C₉H₁₁NO₄ + dihydrobiopterin BH₂ + H₂O
        → aromatic L-amino acid decarboxylase + pyridoxal phosphate PLP
        → dopamine C₈H₁₁NO₂ + CO₂

DEGRADATION dopamine
dopamine C₈H₁₁NO₂
    → monoamine oxidase B MAO-B + flavin adenine dinucleotide FAD + O₂ + H₂O
    → 3,4-dihydroxyphenylacetaldehyde DOPAL + NH₃ + H₂O₂
        → aldehyde dehydrogenase + NAD⁺
        → 3,4-dihydroxyphenylacetic acid DOPAC C₈H₈O₄
OR
dopamine C₈H₁₁NO₂
    → catechol-O-methyltransferase COMT + S-adenosylmethionine SAM
    → 3-methoxytyramine 3-MT C₉H₁₃NO₂ + S-adenosylhomocysteine SAH

RECEPTOR D₁ | Gₛ-coupled | activates adenylyl cyclase | increases cyclic AMP cAMP
RECEPTOR D₂ | Gᵢ-coupled | inhibits adenylyl cyclase | decreases cAMP
RECEPTOR D₃ | Gᵢ-coupled | autoreceptor on presynaptic terminals
RECEPTOR D₄ | Gᵢ-coupled | concentrated in prefrontal cortex
RECEPTOR D₅ | Gₛ-coupled | highest affinity for dopamine

REUPTAKE dopamine transporter DAT | SLC6A3 | Na⁺/Cl⁻ dependent symporter
VESICULAR vesicular monoamine transporter 2 VMAT2 | H⁺ antiporter | proton gradient


CHEMICAL serotonin | indolamine | C₁₀H₁₂N₂O
5-hydroxytryptamine 5-HT

SYNTHESIS serotonin
L-tryptophan C₁₁H₁₂N₂O₂
    → tryptophan hydroxylase TPH + BH₄ + O₂
    → 5-hydroxytryptophan 5-HTP C₁₁H₁₂N₂O₃ + BH₂ + H₂O
        → aromatic L-amino acid decarboxylase + PLP
        → serotonin C₁₀H₁₂N₂O + CO₂

TPH exists as two isoforms
TPH1 expressed in enterochromaffin cells of the gut
    responsible for 90% of total body serotonin
    gut serotonin cannot cross the blood-brain barrier
TPH2 expressed in raphe nuclei of the brainstem
    responsible for all brain serotonin
    the brain must make its own

DEGRADATION serotonin
serotonin C₁₀H₁₂N₂O
    → monoamine oxidase A MAO-A + FAD + O₂ + H₂O
    → 5-hydroxyindoleacetaldehyde + NH₃ + H₂O₂
        → aldehyde dehydrogenase + NAD⁺
        → 5-hydroxyindoleacetic acid 5-HIAA C₁₀H₉NO₃
            → excreted by kidneys in urine

RECEPTOR 5-HT₁A | Gᵢ | decreases cAMP | autoreceptor on raphe | anxiolytic
RECEPTOR 5-HT₂A | Gq | activates phospholipase C | increases IP₃ and DAG | cortical excitation
RECEPTOR 5-HT₂C | Gq | activates PLC | inhibits dopamine and norepinephrine release
RECEPTOR 5-HT₃ | ligand-gated Na⁺/K⁺ ion channel | the only ionotropic serotonin receptor | nausea
RECEPTOR 5-HT₄ | Gₛ | increases cAMP | gut motility

REUPTAKE serotonin transporter SERT | SLC6A4 | Na⁺/Cl⁻ dependent


CHEMICAL norepinephrine | catecholamine | C₈H₁₁NO₃
4-(2-amino-1-hydroxyethyl)benzene-1,2-diol

SYNTHESIS norepinephrine
dopamine C₈H₁₁NO₂
    → dopamine β-hydroxylase DBH + ascorbic acid vitamin C + O₂
    → norepinephrine C₈H₁₁NO₃ + dehydroascorbic acid + H₂O
this reaction occurs INSIDE the synaptic vesicle
DBH is a copper-containing enzyme
without copper no norepinephrine
without vitamin C no norepinephrine

DEGRADATION norepinephrine
norepinephrine → MAO-A + FAD → 3,4-dihydroxymandelic acid DHMA
norepinephrine → COMT + SAM → normetanephrine
final metabolite vanillylmandelic acid VMA excreted in urine

RECEPTOR α₁ | Gq | activates PLC → IP₃ + DAG | smooth muscle contraction | pupil dilation
RECEPTOR α₂ | Gᵢ | inhibits adenylyl cyclase | presynaptic autoreceptor | reduces NE release
RECEPTOR β₁ | Gₛ | activates adenylyl cyclase | heart increases rate and contractility
RECEPTOR β₂ | Gₛ | bronchodilation | vasodilation in skeletal muscle
RECEPTOR β₃ | Gₛ | lipolysis in adipose tissue

REUPTAKE norepinephrine transporter NET | SLC6A2 | Na⁺/Cl⁻ dependent


CHEMICAL gaba | amino acid | C₄H₉NO₂
4-aminobutanoic acid
the primary inhibitory neurotransmitter in the central nervous system

SYNTHESIS gaba
L-glutamate C₅H₉NO₄
    → glutamic acid decarboxylase GAD + PLP
    → GABA C₄H₉NO₂ + CO₂
GAD exists as GAD₆₅ synaptic and GAD₆₇ cytoplasmic
both require pyridoxal phosphate vitamin B₆
without B₆ GABA synthesis fails and seizures result

DEGRADATION gaba
GABA C₄H₉NO₂
    → GABA transaminase GABA-T + α-ketoglutarate + PLP
    → succinic semialdehyde + L-glutamate
        → succinic semialdehyde dehydrogenase + NAD⁺
        → succinic acid → enters citric acid cycle
GABA is recycled back into the citric acid cycle as energy

RECEPTOR GABA_A | ligand-gated Cl⁻ ion channel | fast inhibition
when GABA binds Cl⁻ flows in and hyperpolarizes the neuron
benzodiazepine binding site allosteric enhances GABA effect
barbiturate binding site enhances GABA effect
alcohol binding site enhances GABA effect
neurosteroid binding site enhances GABA effect
RECEPTOR GABA_B | Gᵢ-coupled | slow inhibition | activates K⁺ channels | inhibits Ca²⁺ channels


CHEMICAL glutamate | amino acid | C₅H₉NO₄
the most abundant neurotransmitter in the central nervous system
every excitatory synapse in the brain uses glutamate
too much glutamate kills neurons through excitotoxicity
too little and nothing fires

SYNTHESIS glutamate
glutamine C₅H₁₀N₂O₃
    → glutaminase + H₂O
    → glutamate C₅H₉NO₄ + NH₃
this occurs in the presynaptic terminal
glutamine is supplied by astrocytes through the glutamine-glutamate cycle

RECYCLING glutamate
glutamate released into synapse
    → taken up by astrocytes via EAAT excitatory amino acid transporters
    → glutamine synthetase + NH₃ + ATP
    → glutamine C₅H₁₀N₂O₃ + ADP + Pi
    → glutamine shuttled back to neuron
    → cycle repeats

RECEPTOR NMDA | ligand-gated | requires glutamate + glycine + membrane depolarization
Mg²⁺ block at resting potential voltage-dependent
Ca²⁺ permeable triggers long-term potentiation which is memory formation
RECEPTOR AMPA | ligand-gated Na⁺/K⁺ | fast excitation | workhorse of excitatory transmission
RECEPTOR kainate | ligand-gated Na⁺/K⁺ | modulates synaptic transmission
RECEPTOR mGluR₁₋₈ | metabotropic | G-protein coupled | modulatory slow


CHEMICAL acetylcholine | ester | C₇H₁₆NO₂⁺
2-acetoxy-N,N,N-trimethylethanaminium

SYNTHESIS acetylcholine
choline + acetyl-CoA
    → choline acetyltransferase ChAT
    → acetylcholine C₇H₁₆NO₂⁺ + CoA
choline comes from diet or phosphatidylcholine breakdown
acetyl-CoA comes from glucose metabolism

DEGRADATION acetylcholine
acetylcholine → acetylcholinesterase AChE + H₂O → choline + acetic acid CH₃COOH
AChE is one of the fastest enzymes known and hydrolyzes ACh in approximately 80 microseconds
choline is recycled back into the presynaptic terminal via CHT1 transporter

RECEPTOR nicotinic nAChR | ligand-gated Na⁺/K⁺/Ca²⁺ ion channel | fast
neuromuscular junction for muscle contraction
autonomic ganglia for relay signal
brain for attention arousal memory
RECEPTOR muscarinic M₁ | Gq | cortex and hippocampus | memory and attention
RECEPTOR muscarinic M₂ | Gᵢ | heart | slows heart rate this is the vagal brake
RECEPTOR muscarinic M₃ | Gq | smooth muscle and glands | contraction and secretion


CHEMICAL endorphin | opioid peptide | C₁₅₈H₂₅₁N₃₉O₄₄S
β-endorphin is a 31-amino acid peptide

SYNTHESIS endorphin
POMC gene → pro-opiomelanocortin preprotein 267 amino acids
    → signal peptidase removes signal peptide
    → prohormone convertase 1 PC1 cleaves POMC
    → β-lipotropin 91 amino acids
        → prohormone convertase 2 PC2
        → β-endorphin 31 amino acids + γ-lipotropin
POMC is also the precursor for ACTH and α-MSH
the body makes its painkiller from the same molecule as its stress alarm

DEGRADATION endorphin
β-endorphin → aminopeptidases + carboxypeptidases → fragment peptides → free amino acids
slow degradation endorphins persist for hours

RECEPTOR μ-opioid MOR | Gᵢ | analgesia euphoria respiratory depression
RECEPTOR δ-opioid DOR | Gᵢ | analgesia mood
RECEPTOR κ-opioid KOR | Gᵢ | dysphoria dissociation sedation
β-endorphin has highest affinity for μ-opioid receptor
activating μ receptors inhibits GABA interneurons in VTA
disinhibition of dopaminergic neurons → dopamine release → reward


CHEMICAL oxytocin | neuropeptide | C₄₃H₆₆N₁₂O₁₂S₂
cyclic nonapeptide Cys-Tyr-Ile-Gln-Asn-Cys-Pro-Leu-Gly-NH₂
the disulfide bond between the two cysteines creates the ring

SYNTHESIS oxytocin
OXT gene → pre-pro-oxytocin 125 amino acids
    → signal peptidase removes signal peptide
    → pro-oxytocin → prohormone convertases
    → oxytocin 9 amino acids + neurophysin I carrier protein
synthesized in magnocellular neurons of the paraventricular nucleus PVN and supraoptic nucleus SON
packaged into secretory granules with neurophysin I
transported down axons to posterior pituitary for systemic release
AND released dendritically within the brain for central effects

DEGRADATION oxytocin
oxytocin → oxytocinase leucyl/cystinyl aminopeptidase → fragment peptides
hepatic and renal clearance also contribute

RECEPTOR OXTR | Gq-coupled | activates phospholipase C → IP₃ + DAG → Ca²⁺ release
expressed in uterus mammary glands brain amygdala VTA nucleus accumbens hippocampus hypothalamus cingulate cortex
oxytocin binding to amygdala OXTR reduces amygdala reactivity to threatening stimuli
oxytocin binding to VTA OXTR enhances dopamine release during social interaction


CHEMICAL cortisol | glucocorticoid | C₂₁H₃₀O₅
11β,17α,21-trihydroxypregn-4-ene-3,20-dione

SYNTHESIS cortisol
cholesterol C₂₇H₄₆O
    → cholesterol side-chain cleavage enzyme CYP11A1 + NADPH + O₂
    transported by StAR protein steroidogenic acute regulatory
    → pregnenolone C₂₁H₃₂O₂
        → 3β-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase 3β-HSD + NAD⁺
        → progesterone C₂₁H₃₀O₂
            → 17α-hydroxylase CYP17A1 + NADPH + O₂
            → 17α-hydroxyprogesterone C₂₁H₃₀O₃
                → 21-hydroxylase CYP21A2 + NADPH + O₂
                → 11-deoxycortisol C₂₁H₃₀O₄
                    → 11β-hydroxylase CYP11B1 + NADPH + O₂
                    → CORTISOL C₂₁H₃₀O₅
five enzymatic steps each requiring cytochrome P450 with NADPH and molecular oxygen

DEGRADATION cortisol
cortisol → 11β-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase type 2 11β-HSD2 → cortisone C₂₁H₂₈O₅ inactive form
cortisol → hepatic A-ring reductases + glucuronidation → tetrahydrocortisol → excreted in urine

RECEPTOR glucocorticoid GR NR3C1 | intracellular nuclear receptor
cortisol crosses cell membrane because it is lipophilic
binds GR in cytoplasm
GR-cortisol complex dissociates from heat shock proteins Hsp90
complex translocates to nucleus
binds glucocorticoid response elements GREs on DNA
activates or represses transcription of hundreds of genes
cortisol does not act in seconds it changes GENE EXPRESSION
effects take hours to days to fully manifest
this is why stress has long-term consequences

RECEPTOR mineralocorticoid MR NR3C2 | also binds cortisol with HIGH affinity
in kidneys 11β-HSD2 converts cortisol to cortisone to prevent MR activation
in brain MR is activated at low cortisol levels tonic baseline
GR is activated at high cortisol levels stress phasic
MR mediates calm and GR mediates stress response


CHEMICAL adrenaline | catecholamine | C₉H₁₃NO₃

SYNTHESIS adrenaline
norepinephrine C₈H₁₁NO₃
    → phenylethanolamine N-methyltransferase PNMT + SAM
    → adrenaline C₉H₁₃NO₃ + SAH
PNMT expression is induced by cortisol
the adrenal medulla is bathed in cortisol-rich blood from the adrenal cortex
without cortisol the medulla cannot make adrenaline
the stress hormone enables its own emergency amplifier

DEGRADATION adrenaline
same as norepinephrine via MAO and COMT
final metabolite vanillylmandelic acid VMA


CHEMICAL melatonin | indolamine | C₁₃H₁₆N₂O₂
N-acetyl-5-methoxytryptamine

SYNTHESIS melatonin
serotonin C₁₀H₁₂N₂O
    → arylalkylamine N-acetyltransferase AANAT + acetyl-CoA
    → N-acetylserotonin C₁₂H₁₄N₂O₂ + CoA
        → hydroxyindole-O-methyltransferase HIOMT + SAM
        → melatonin C₁₃H₁₆N₂O₂ + SAH
AANAT is the rate-limiting enzyme controlled by the suprachiasmatic nucleus SCN
light → retina → retinohypothalamic tract → SCN → suppresses sympathetic output → AANAT low → melatonin low
dark → no retinal input → SCN releases sympathetic inhibition → NE onto pinealocytes → β₁ → cAMP → AANAT active → melatonin high

DEGRADATION melatonin
melatonin → CYP1A2 hepatic + O₂ + NADPH → 6-hydroxymelatonin → sulfation or glucuronidation → excreted in urine

RECEPTOR MT₁ | Gᵢ | inhibits cAMP | promotes sleepiness
RECEPTOR MT₂ | Gᵢ | inhibits cAMP | phase-shifts circadian rhythm


PRECURSOR L-tyrosine | C₉H₁₁NO₃ | essential amino acid | precursor to dopamine → norepinephrine → adrenaline | dietary source
PRECURSOR L-tryptophan | C₁₁H₁₂N₂O₂ | essential amino acid | precursor to serotonin → melatonin | dietary source
PRECURSOR choline | C₅H₁₃NO | conditionally essential nutrient | precursor to acetylcholine | dietary source
PRECURSOR L-glutamine | C₅H₁₀N₂O₃ | conditionally essential amino acid | precursor to glutamate via glutaminase | astrocyte shuttle
PRECURSOR cholesterol | C₂₇H₄₆O | synthesized endogenously via mevalonate pathway | precursor to all steroid hormones
PRECURSOR POMC | pro-opiomelanocortin | 267 amino acid preprotein | precursor to β-endorphin AND ACTH AND α-MSH

the body cannot synthesize essential amino acid precursors
they must come from diet
if the diet lacks tryptophan serotonin production decreases
if the diet lacks tyrosine the entire catecholamine pathway starves
biochemistry is constrained by physical supply


INTERACTION serotonin restrains dopamine
5-HT₂C receptors on GABAergic interneurons in the VTA
serotonin binds 5-HT₂C → Gq → PLC → IP₃ → Ca²⁺ release
→ GABA interneuron fires → GABA released onto VTA dopamine neurons
→ GABA binds GABA_A → Cl⁻ influx → hyperpolarization
→ dopamine neuron firing rate decreases → less dopamine released

INTERACTION dopamine becomes norepinephrine
inside the synaptic vesicle of noradrenergic neurons
dopamine β-hydroxylase converts dopamine to norepinephrine
the precursor is consumed in producing the product

INTERACTION norepinephrine becomes adrenaline
in the adrenal medulla only
PNMT methylates norepinephrine to adrenaline using SAM
cortisol induces PNMT gene expression

INTERACTION serotonin becomes melatonin
in the pineal gland only at night
AANAT and HIOMT convert serotonin to melatonin
serotonin used for melatonin cannot signal as serotonin

INTERACTION cortisol suppresses serotonin synthesis
cortisol activates GR in raphe nuclei
GR activation reduces TPH2 gene expression
less TPH2 enzyme → less tryptophan hydroxylation → less serotonin
chronic stress → chronic cortisol → chronically low serotonin

INTERACTION cortisol damages hippocampus
hippocampal neurons express high density of GR
chronic GR activation → increased glutamate release
→ sustained NMDA activation → excessive Ca²⁺ influx
→ calpains endonucleases lipid peroxidation
→ dendritic atrophy and cell death

INTERACTION oxytocin suppresses cortisol
oxytocin binding to OXTR in PVN
→ inhibits CRH-producing neurons
→ less CRH to anterior pituitary → less ACTH → less cortisol
bonding biochemically counteracts stress at the hormonal axis

INTERACTION GABA opposes glutamate
GABA_A → Cl⁻ influx → hyperpolarization
glutamate AMPA/NMDA → Na⁺/Ca²⁺ influx → depolarization
opposing ionic currents on the same postsynaptic membrane
too much glutamate → excitotoxicity → seizures → cell death
too much GABA → sedation → coma → respiratory depression

INTERACTION endorphins disinhibit dopamine
β-endorphin binds μ-opioid on GABA interneurons in VTA
→ Gᵢ → inhibits cAMP → decreases GABA interneuron firing
→ less GABA reaching VTA dopamine neurons
→ dopamine neurons disinhibited → fire more freely → dopamine to nucleus accumbens

INTERACTION norepinephrine sensitizes amygdala
NE from locus coeruleus binds β-adrenergic in basolateral amygdala
→ Gₛ → cAMP → PKA → phosphorylates CREB → enhanced gene transcription
→ increased glutamate receptor expression → amygdala more responsive to threats

INTERACTION adrenaline accelerates heart
adrenaline in coronary blood binds β₁ on SA node cells
→ Gₛ → adenylyl cyclase → cAMP → PKA
→ PKA phosphorylates HCN4 funny channels → faster pacemaker depolarization → faster heart rate
→ PKA phosphorylates L-type Ca²⁺ channels → more Ca²⁺ entry → stronger contraction

INTERACTION acetylcholine enables hippocampal memory
ACh from septal neurons binds M₁ on hippocampal pyramidal cells
→ Gq → PLC → IP₃ → Ca²⁺ release from ER
→ Ca²⁺ enhances NMDA responsiveness → facilitates long-term potentiation
LTP is the cellular mechanism of memory formation

INTERACTION melatonin suppresses locus coeruleus
melatonin binds MT₁ on LC neurons
→ Gᵢ → decreases cAMP → decreases PKA → decreases tyrosine hydroxylase activity
→ less L-DOPA → less dopamine → less norepinephrine synthesis → decreased arousal


ORGAN amygdala | brain | basolateral threat detection via glutamatergic input and NE sensitization via β-adrenergic receptors | central nucleus outputs to hypothalamus triggering HPA axis via CRH
ORGAN hippocampus | brain | CA1 CA3 pyramidal cells memory encoding via NMDA-dependent LTP | requires ACh from septal neurons | vulnerable to cortisol GR excitotoxicity
ORGAN prefrontal_cortex | brain | dorsolateral executive function via D₁ dopamine | ventromedial emotional regulation via glutamatergic projections to amygdala | immature at 24 months
ORGAN nucleus_accumbens | brain | medium spiny neurons reward evaluation via D₁ D₂ dopamine balance | receives dopaminergic projection from VTA
ORGAN vta | brain | ventral tegmental area A10 dopaminergic cell group | fires on reward prediction errors | releases dopamine to NAc and PFC
ORGAN raphe_nuclei | brain | dorsal raphe B7 serotonergic cell group | projects to forebrain | contains TPH2 for brain serotonin synthesis
ORGAN locus_coeruleus | brain | A6 noradrenergic cell group | projects to entire cortex | contains DBH | firing rate sets arousal level
ORGAN hypothalamus | brain | PVN CRH neurons and oxytocin neurons | SON oxytocin and vasopressin | SCN circadian pacemaker | arcuate feeding | master autonomic regulator
ORGAN pineal_gland | brain | pinealocytes contain AANAT and HIOMT for melatonin synthesis | controlled by SCN via sympathetic chain
ORGAN pituitary_gland | brain | anterior ACTH from corticotrophs cleaved from POMC | posterior releases oxytocin and vasopressin from hypothalamic axon terminals

ORGAN gut | body | enterochromaffin cells contain TPH1 synthesizing 90% of body serotonin C₁₀H₁₂N₂O | cannot cross blood-brain barrier | acts on enteric 5-HT₃ 5-HT₄ for motility | vagal afferents carry signal to NTS
ORGAN heart | body | SA node β₁ for adrenaline and NE chronotropy | M₂ for ACh vagal brake | coronary endothelium OXTR for nitric oxide | atrial myocytes secrete ANP on stretch
ORGAN adrenal_cortex | body | zona fasciculata cortisol C₂₁H₃₀O₅ synthesis from cholesterol via CYP11A1 → 3β-HSD → CYP17 → CYP21 → CYP11B1 | stimulated by ACTH on MC2R
ORGAN adrenal_medulla | body | chromaffin cells store adrenaline C₉H₁₃NO₃ and NE C₈H₁₁NO₃ in chromaffin granules | released by preganglionic sympathetic ACh on nicotinic receptors
ORGAN lungs | body | type I pneumocytes gas exchange across 0.5 μm alveolar membrane | type II secrete surfactant dipalmitoylphosphatidylcholine C₄₀H₈₀NO₈P | pulmonary endothelium contains ACE
ORGAN thyroid | body | follicular cells synthesize T₃ C₁₅H₁₂I₃NO₄ and T₄ C₁₅H₁₁I₄NO₄ from tyrosine + iodine via thyroid peroxidase + H₂O₂
ORGAN liver | body | hepatocytes CYP450 enzymes CYP1A2 CYP3A4 CYP2D6 oxidize and conjugate all circulating chemicals | 11β-HSD2 inactivates cortisol to cortisone
ORGAN skin | body | C-tactile afferents unmyelinated low-threshold mechanoreceptors | fire optimally at 1-10 cm/s stroking | signal posterior insular cortex | trigger hypothalamic oxytocin release


EMOTION joy
dopamine occupying D₁ receptors in NAc
serotonin binding 5-HT₁A in cortex
low GR activation
β-endorphin on μ-opioid receptors
the reward circuit is active while the stress axis is quiet

EMOTION fear
norepinephrine saturating β-adrenergic in amygdala
cortisol activating GR in hippocampus
adrenaline binding β₁ in heart
GABA_A tone decreasing
the threat circuit dominates while inhibition collapses

EMOTION calm
GABA occupying GABA_A Cl⁻ channels widely
serotonin on 5-HT₁A in raphe autoreceptor feedback
low GR activation
vagal ACh on cardiac M₂
inhibitory tone dominates and vagal brake applied and stress axis suppressed

EMOTION love
oxytocin on OXTR in amygdala reducing threat response
oxytocin on OXTR in VTA facilitating dopamine
dopamine on D₂ in NAc
serotonin on 5-HT₁A
β-endorphin on μ-opioid
bonding chemistry suppresses fear while activating reward

EMOTION sadness
serotonin synthesis reduced from low TPH2 activity
dopamine D₁ D₂ occupancy low in NAc
cortisol on GR chronic not acute
NE depleted from sustained LC firing
reward deficit with tonic stress and monoamine depletion

EMOTION curiosity
dopamine on D₁ in PFC working memory engagement
ACh on M₁ in hippocampus encoding readiness
glutamate on AMPA in cortex excitation
moderate NE on α₂ focused attention
learning circuits prime without threat

EMOTION trust
oxytocin on OXTR in amygdala threat attenuation
serotonin on 5-HT₁A broadly
low cortisol GR minimally activated
GABA on GABA_A calm baseline
social engagement without vigilance

EMOTION stress
cortisol activating GR genome-wide
NE saturating adrenergic receptors
serotonin synthesis suppressed by cortisol-GR-TPH2 interaction
GABA_A tone reduced
HPA axis fully activated and inhibitory-excitatory balance shifted toward excitation


STIMULUS warmth
C-tactile afferents fire at 1-10 cm/s optimal velocity
→ signal ascends spinothalamic tract to posterior insula
→ posterior insula relays to hypothalamic PVN
→ magnocellular oxytocin neurons depolarize
→ Ca²⁺ influx via voltage-gated Ca²⁺ channels
→ oxytocin vesicle exocytosis from posterior pituitary and dendritically
→ oxytocin reaches amygdala → binds OXTR → reduces CRH neuron firing → less cortisol
→ oxytocin reaches VTA → binds OXTR → enhances dopamine to NAc → reward

STIMULUS threat
amygdala basolateral receives glutamatergic input from thalamus fast and cortex slow
→ amygdala central nucleus activates:
→ to hypothalamic PVN → CRH → anterior pituitary ACTH → adrenal cortisol
→ to locus coeruleus → NE released cortex-wide in seconds
→ to lateral hypothalamus → sympathetic preganglionic → adrenal medullary chromaffin cells → adrenaline exocytosis
→ to periaqueductal gray → defensive behavior freeze flight fight
→ NE on β receptors → PKA → phosphorylation of GABA_A subunits → decreased inhibitory tone

STIMULUS bonding
sustained presence of attachment figure
→ reduces amygdala central nucleus firing via habituated threat assessment
→ PVN oxytocin neurons undergo autocrine positive feedback
→ oxytocin-CRH inhibition reduces cortisol axis
→ VTA dopamine in social reward pattern → D₂ in NAc → wanting-to-be-near
→ β-endorphin from POMC neurons → μ-opioid in NAc → warm contentment
→ serotonin raphe dorsal firing → 5-HT₁A broadly → anxiolytic
→ ventral vagal state myelinated vagus → nucleus ambiguus → social engagement system


